Sample: b'976testa_ROMANIA'
 [1 1 ROMANIA 1] COMELF H1 PROFIT RISE BELOW TARGET . [2 2 BUCHAREST 2] 1996-08-30 [1 Romanian 1] listed state engineer Comelf said it almost doubled six-month output , with net profit rising by 33 percent to 1.069 billion lei . But the company complained inflation and the artificially high rate of the leu cut profit margins on exports , keeping profits well below its forecast of 1.4 billion lei . Comelf 's six-month output rose to 4,378 tonnes of equipment from 2,684 tonnes in the equivalent period in 1995 , the company report to the [3 3 Bucharest 3] stock exchange showed . Comelf , based in the central [4 4 Transylvanian 4] town of [5 5 Bistrita 5] , manufactures water purification equipment , machinery for the thermal power sector and other equipment . " In the first six months of 1996 we concentrated on increasing the volume of our output and exports in particular and improving the quality of our products , " the report said . From January to June Comelf exported 59 percent of its output , up from 37.3 percent in the same period last year . The company said higher than anticipated inflation and rising raw materials and wage costs also hit profits . Year-on-year inflation , initially estimated at 20 percent in December , was 33.8 percent in June , higher than a revised end-year forecast of 30 percent . The 12 month figure quickened to 40.3 percent in July . The leu currency has slipped only gradually this year , and is currently quoted at an official rate of 3,162 to the dollar , well below the 3,550 retail price that exporters say is more realistic . -- Luli Popescu , Bucharest Newsroom 40-1 3120264

[1 1 NEW YORK 1] 1996-08-30 NYMEX refined product prices lingered at session lows amid slim volume before the close while crude experienced lackluster buying ahead of the [2 1 U.S. 2 Labor Day 2] weekend , traders said . " There was some profit-taking early on , and it 's just sitting there , " a [3 3 Texas 3] trader said of heating oil 's and gasoline 's losses . September heating oil stood 1.02 cents lower at 62.65 cents a gallon . Heat hit a session low of 62.45 shortly before the close . September gasoline stood 0.87 cent lower at 62.85 cents a gallon . Friday 's low in September gasoline was 62.75 . Traders also said players were selling refined products in favor of crude ahead of the front month 's Friday expiry in the refined products . October crude stood eight cents higher at $ 22.23 barrel . Buying interest in crude did not have enough conviction to send it much higher since many players had left early to start the [4 4 Labor Day 4] holiday weekend , traders said .  [1 1 U.S. 1] debt futures end lower , shaken by 1 Chicago NAPM . [2 2 CHICAGO 2] 1996-08-30 [3 3 U.S. 3] debt futures finished a shortened pre-holiday session sharply lower , as the markets were shaken by a stronger than expected rise in the August [4 4 National Association of Purchasing Management 4] ( NAPM ) index for the [5 5 Chicago 5] area , traders and analysts said . The August 2 Chicago NAPM rose 8.8 points to 60.0 , its highest level since 62.6 in February 1995 and the largest monthly rise since December 1993 . Primary dealers immediately sold [6 6 Eurodollar 6] and bond futures , after the market on average was expecting the index to rise marginally to 51.9 from July 's 51.2 . Traders also said [7 7 Japanese 7] investors were unwinding long [8 8 Eurodollar 8] futures / short swaps , and that heavy put buying helped pressure 3 Eurodollars to lower levels before the close . One [9 9 U.S. 9] firm bought 35,000 September 97 mid-curve put options at a strike price of 93.25 to 93.30 in the last two sessions , while a [10 10 French 10] firm bought 4,000 September 93.30 to 93.32 put spreads . " Even before the data came out , we were seeing put buying , " one floor trader said . Meanwhile , funds were reportedly good sellers of five-year notes . Rumors circulated that the [11 11 Federal Reserve 11] was buying five-year notes , and that a renowned hedge fund manager was buying 10-year notes in the cash markets . However , December T-bonds ended below a major trendline level at 106-26/32 , as the yield in the cash bond market set its highest monthly close since April 1995 at 7.12 percent , one analyst said . December bonds blew through the July 30 low of 107-06/32 , even though conditions were slightly oversold , traders said . The December calendar spread continued to widen , also reflecting the market 's fear of rising inflation . While the market continues to price-in higher [12 12 U.S. 12] interest rates , there was little conviction to the theory that the [13 13 Federal Reserve 13] would tighten rates before the next [14 14 Federal Open Market Committee 14] meeting on September 24 . [15 15 Federal Reserve 15] governor [16 16 Lawrence Lindsey 16] , speaking on [17 17 U.S. 17] cable television network [18 18 CNBC 18] , said the [19 19 U.S. 19] economy appears on balance to be a bit strong , adding the central bank would not curb growth provided inflation remains in check . Earlier in the day , [20 20 Fed 20] chairman [21 21 Alan Greenspan 21] said at the annual [1 Jackson Hole 1] symposium that the goal of price stability is within reach for major nations . Traders said the [22 22 Fed 22] 's decision to adopt a tightening bias at the July [23 23 FOMC 23] meeting has cast more focus on every piece of [24 24 U.S. 24] economic news . " The [25 25 Fed 25] 's stance has really sensitized us to all this data , " one analyst said . " The revisions to GDP , for example , may not have attracted a lot of attention . " At the end of pit trade , December bonds were off 27/32 at 106-25/32 , 10-year notes down 21/32 at 105-17/32 , munibonds off 17/32 at 111-20/32 , December [26 26 Eurodollars 26] were down 11 bps at 93.94 , March 4 Eurodollars were off 13 bps at 93.72 and March T-bills were down 12 bps at 94.33 .

 Douglas & Lomason shares rise on merger . [1 1 FARMINGTON HILLS 1] , Mich . 1996-08-30 Shares of Douglas & Lomason Co were up 4-1/2 at 30-5/8 Friday afternoon after Thursday 's announcement that the vehicle seat maker had agreed to be acquired by [1 Magna International Inc 1] for $ 31 a share , or $ 135 million . [2 2 Magna 2] was up 1/8 to 48-1/4 on the [3 3 New York Stock Exchange 3] . Douglas & Lomason has 4.45 million common shares outstanding , some of which are option shares to be purchased at exercise prices less than the $ 31 offered price . The acquisition will beef up [4 4 Markham 4] , Ontario-based [5 5 Magna 5] 's [6 6 North American 6] car and truck seating business , allowing it to better compete with [7 7 Johnson Controls Inc 7] and Lear Corp . Family-controlled Douglas & Lomason , which had 1995 revenue of $ 561 million , was finding it more difficult to compete for new seating contracts from vehicle makers , said James Hoey , chief financial officer . " Unfortunately , in the auto industry these days , a $ 500 million company is not a big company anymore , " Hoey said . " This merger makes us much more competitive . " He added that Douglas & Lomason 's top executives have been asked to stay on with [8 8 Magna 8] after the merger , though their future roles have not yet been defined . Douglas & Lomason 's profits were hurt in the past year by model changeovers , which had reduced production at some important customers , but are now recovering , analysts said . The company earned $ 11.2 million on sales of $ 299 million in the first six months of 1996 , up from year-earlier earnings of $ 4.7 million on sales of $ 285.7 million . [9 9 Ford 9] plans to cut its roster of 2,300 tier-one suppliers -- those it deals with directly -- in half over the next five years . " The deal really levels the seating field somewhat , " said John Casesa of Schroder Wertheim & Co . " It should give [10 10 Magna 10] the critical mass to be a bigger player in that market . " [11 11 Magna 11] 's traditional strength has been instrument panels , door panels and other interior components . [12 12 Magna 12] , [13 13 Johnson Controls 13] and Lear have been working to build up their capabilties to supply complete interiors to automakers , including seats , instrument panels , door panels carpeting and headliners .

Larisa Sayenko [2 2 MINSK 2] 1996-08-30 A senior [3 3 Belarus 3] politician accused President [4 4 Alexander Lukashenko 4] on Friday of attempting to set up a dictatorship in the former [5 5 Soviet 5] republic . The speaker of the [6 6 Belarus 6] parliament , Semyon Sharetsky , told [7 7 Reuters 7] that a draft constitution , due to be put to a national referendum on November 7 , would dangerously increase the powers of the ruler . " The world community should not be indifferent to the fact that President [8 8 Lukashenko 8] , who leads this [9 9 European 9] state of 10 million people , is trying to establish a dictatorship with his new constitution , " Sharetsky said . The new constitution calls for a two-chamber parliament with a 110-seat majority-elected house of representatives and a regionally-represented senate with a third of its members named by the president . [10 10 Lukashenko 10] 's aides shrugged off Sharetsky 's charge . " If there was a dictatorship they would n't have the right to say things like this , " Sergei Posukhov , [11 11 Lukashenko 11] 's political adviser , told [12 12 Reuters 12] . " The people have asked us to establish order and that 's our main aim . " [13 13 Lukashenko 13] , 41 , won presidential polls in 1994 on promises to restore order , fight corruption and repair the strong links with [14 14 Russia 14] that were disrupted by the collapse of the [15 15 Soviet Union 15] . But during his period in office he has battled against nationalist opponents , trade unions and parliament and [1 Sharetsky 1] said the current parliament was ready to try to impeach him . " This constitution , which has been prepared in secret , aims to gather all power in one man 's hands , " he said . " We should not be fooled by his quasi-democratic rhetoric and his methods , like this referendum . " [16 16 Lukashenko 16] signed a pact with [17 17 Moscow 17] in April to create a strong economic and political union which he believes could grow into a federation . But nationalist groups , scared by the prospect of renewed [18 18 Moscow 18] domination and [19 19 Russia 19] 's backing for [20 20 Lukashenko 20] , protested against the deal . [21 21 Lukashenko 21] responded by cracking down on the nationalist opposition and jailing nearly 200 people for taking part in demonstrations against the pact . The [22 22 United States 22] last week granted political asylum to two opposition leaders , Zenon Poznyak and Sergei Naumchik .

 [1 1 Tajik 1] troops now control devastated town . Yuri Kushko [2 2 TAVILDARA 2] , [3 3 Tajikistan 3] 1996-08-30 [4 4 Tajik 4] government troops now control of the strategically vital town of [5 5 Tavildara 5] after driving out [6 6 Islamic 6] rebels , but sporadic gunfire still echoed in the nearby [7 7 Pamir 7] mountains on Friday . The commander-in-chief of [8 8 Tajikistan 8] 's armed forces , Major-General Nikolai Sherbatov , took a group of journalists by helicopter to the remote , and now devastated , town to show that his forces held it . He said his troops took [9 9 Tavildara 9] without casualties on August 23 , but the crack of sniper and machinegun fire revealed the presence of opposition fighters in the surrounding mountains . Sherbatov said the rebels were located about three km ( two miles ) east of [10 10 Tavildara 10] around the village of Layron . [11 11 Tavildara 11] , 200 km ( 120 miles ) east of the capital [12 12 Dushanbe 12] , was in ruins . Shells had smashed roofs and windows and empty shell cases littered the streets . The town straddles a strategically important road linking government and rebel-held territory and has fallen succesively to both sides in a bloody tug-of-war which began last February . [13 13 Tajikistan 13] , which borders [14 14 Afghanistan 14] and [15 15 China 15] , has been split by a dragging four-year conflict after a civil war between communists and a frail coalition of [16 16 Islamic 16] and liberal groups . Tens of thousands of people have been killed and many more have been displaced in the fighting , which breached a shaky [1 United Nations-sponsored 1] ceasefire . [17 17 Tavildara 17] is now apparently inhabited only by a few old men , women and their grubby , barefoot children . Fruit remained on the trees as there was no one to pick it . " Help me , help me , " said a chorus of women begging soldiers for food . The town 's school and a shop doubling as a warehouse for humanitarian aid were destroyed in the fighting . " We had to build our own earth shelters to survive the fighting , " said Rajab Adinayev , a bearded elderly 1 Tajik in a long white shirt . Although shy in front of the government soldiers , several inhabitants accused government forces of widespread looting of homes and livestock . They also said rebel fighters had looted medicines from the local hospital . One elderly man , who declined to give his name , said two of his sons were now refugees in [18 18 Moscow 18] and the other two had left to fight for the opposition . He also said government soldiers had raped the wife of one of his sons . " It 's not important who holds this town , we just need to stop the war , " he said .

Cofinec CEO Stephen Frater told reporters in a conference call from [3 3 Vienna 3] on Friday before the opening of the bourse that he expects a stronger second half , although the group will not be able to achieve its annual profit goal . " We will not achieve the full 37 million [4 4 French 4] franc ( net ) profit forecast , " Frater said . " Frater declined to give a forecast for the full year , ahead of a supervisory board meeting next week . Cofinec , the first foreign company to list on the [5 5 Budapest 5] bourse , released its consolidated first half figures ( IAS ) this morning . In the conference call , Frater said he regarded Cofinec GDRs -- which are trading below their issue price of 6,425 forints -- as a buying opportunity . " Obviously , at some point it represents a buying opportunity , " Frater said . " I think the reality is that we operate in emerging markets , emerging markets tend to be more volatile . " " My message is that the fundamental strategy of the company , its fundamental market position has not changed . " The group , which operates in [6 6 Hungary 6] , [7 7 Poland 7] and the [8 8 Czech Republic 8] , reported an operating profit before interest of 21.8 million [9 9 French 9] francs compared to 34.1 million in the same six months of 1995 . Cofinec said [3 Petofi 3] general manager Laszlo Sebesvari had submitted his resignation and will be leaving [4 Petofi 4] but will remain on Petofi 's board of directors . " Until a new general manager of Petofi is appointed ... I will in fact move to [12 12 Kecskemet 12] ( site of [5 Petofi 5] printing house ) for the interim and will serve as acting chief executive officer of Petofi , " Frater said . -- [13 13 Budapest 13] newsroom ( 36 1 ) 327 4040

 Far East Gold - Moribund market seen continuing . Mishi Saran [1 1 HONG KONG 1] 1996-08-30 [1 Far East 1] gold traders thumped foreheads in frustration at the market 's foot-dragging this week and forecast on Friday that next week would not be much better . The [2 2 Southeast Asian 2] gold market was more or less a photo-fit picture of the previous week 's position with activity slow and bullion prices trapped in a well-worn range awaiting a seasonal upturn in demand and prices into the fourth quarter . [3 3 Singapore 3] premiums for [4 4 Australian 4] kilo bars were quoted unchanged at between 25-45 cents an ounce over spot loco [5 5 London 5] prices , with [6 6 South Korean 6] and Indonesian-origin premiums also steady at 10-20 cents an ounce . [7 7 Singapore 7] dealers said they were concerned that there had been a marked revival in offers to sell gold by [8 8 South Korean 8] traders , following the distress sales of recent months after the [9 9 Seoul 9] government 's crackdown on bullion arbitrage trade . " I was shocked to see these offers coming in again , though there 's been no indication of price or volume . I dread to think what will happen to the premiums if the [10 10 Koreans 10] start selling in force , " one dealer said . Continued dishoarding of kilo-bars by [11 11 Indonesian 11] sources ahead of next year 's presidential election has also kept a lid on premiums . Gold closed down at $ 387.00 / $ 387.50 an ounce in [12 12 Hong Kong 12] on Friday , versus [13 13 New York 13] 's $ 387.60 / $ 388 finish on Thursday . Dealers said the precious metal eased on a report that the [14 14 International Monetary Fund 14] might sell some of its gold to reduce the debts of the poorest developing countries . Easier silver prices mid-week helped keep spot gold locked in a $ 386 - $ 389 an ounce range , dealers said , but they remained optimistic that the usual seasonal pick-up in jewellery fabrication demand would see gold at $ 395 by end-October . " I still think we 'll see gold at $ 395 by the end of October , in a retracement of the $ 418 - $ 380 move we saw at the start of the year , " one said . Silver , basis the September contract on [15 15 New York 15] 's Comex market , was expected to find support at between $ 5.12 - $ 5.15 an ounce and meet resistance from $ 5.25 - $ 5.30 , they added . September silver closed up $ 0.004 in [16 16 New York 16] on Thursday at $ 5.255 an ounce .

Sample: b'1008testa_Twilight'
 Twilight zone for [1 1 Wall Street 1] as political race heats up . Pierre Belec [1 1 NEW YORK 1] 1996-08-30 For [2 2 Wall Street 2] , this is the season to be cautious as the presidential contest puts the stock market in the twilight zone . President [2 2 Clinton 2] , [3 3 Bob Dole 3] and [4 4 Ross Perot 4] are hitting the road now that the partying is over , and people who have billions of dollars invested in stocks were bracing for political promises that could have an impact on their wealth . Analysts believe that the candidates will add to the market 's list of uncertainties , which already includes the question of whether the [5 5 Federal Reserve 5] will raise interest rates to cool economic growth . They say the politicians will need to promote legislation that helps the economy without scaring the socks off financial markets . " The worst thing that could happen for financial markets is that if [6 6 Clinton 6] and [7 7 Dole 7] start to trade shots in the middle of the ring with one-upmanship , " said [3 Hugh Johnson 3] , chief investment officer at First Albany Corp. " That 's when [4 3 Wall Street 4] will need to worry . " He said that the bond market would be the first to react if the " bidding " intensifies and stocks would quickly drop as interest rates rise . " I do n't think it would imply the collapse of the stock market , unless the rise in rates touches off a dynamic within the market , which would include selling by portfolio managers , redemptions by individuals of mutual funds that would , in turn , pressure the portfolio managers to sell even more stock . " This week , the market weighed [8 8 Dole 8] 's proposal to lower federal income taxes by 15 percent across the board , a package that carries a price tag of $ 548 billion . [9 9 Clinton 9] proposes an $ 8.4 billion re-election agenda that would spare most home-sellers from capital gains taxes and give employers tax incentives to hire people off the welfare rolls . [10 10 Clinton 10] claims [11 11 Dole 11] 's plan would increase the deficit , while the [12 12 White House 12] said some corporate taxes would be raised to offset the cost of the president 's plan . The experts said there are some unusual risks for the market from this year 's political season because the rush to promise tax cuts to win votes could upset [5 4 Wall Street 5] 's expectations that 5 Washington will balance the budget . " The stock market will have to edit the promises and then do a probability study on those edited promises , " said John Geraghty at the consulting firm North American Equity Services . During the past four presidential elections , the candidate that has favoured tax cuts has won . [13 13 Ronald Reagan 13] 's tax cut won him a second four-year term in the [14 14 White House 14] in 1984 , while [15 15 Democrat 15] [16 16 Walter Mondale 16] , who promised higher taxes , lost . [17 17 George Bush 17] became president in 1988 on his no-new-tax campaign and [18 18 Clinton 18] won in 1992 with a promise to fatten workers ' paychecks . The trick , they said , will be for the candidates to continue to convince [6 6 Wall Street 6] that the [19 19 Treasury 19] 's 30-year bond -- the most closely-watched interest rate -- will fall to between 4 percent and 5 percent by the end of the decade . Johnson said that long-term interest rates have already been spooked by the election . The long-term bond jumped this week to 7.13 percent after starting the year at 5.95 percent . The surge of buying in stocks during the last two years has come amid an environment of low interest rates , which has boosted corporate profits . But the market stalled this summer after the [20 20 Dow Jones 20] industrial average set a record high of 5,778.00 points on May 22 . " The market does n't seem to be able to make new highs and it has been back and forth in a fairly horizontal mode which looks like a holding pattern , " said Geraghty . He said the market reflects the political uncertainty , now that [21 21 Dole 21] has sharply narrowed the gap with [22 22 Clinton 22] in the polls . Geraghty said that the one thing that could completely turn the election around are new findings in the 7 Whitewater scandal that would damage the [7 Clintons 7] . " Stocks are on a delicate edge because if something happens that looks like it could upset the presidency , it could throw the political and , to some extent the economic , process into chaos , " Geraghty said . Right now , [8 8 Wall Street 8] is pondering the candidates . " We have an election where there are so many unknown variables that most people will probably want to hold fire , and even take the chance that they will have to pay higher prices for stocks after the November election , than take the risk that a shock to the system will hurt the stock market , " Geraghty said .  Brisk economic reports rattle markets anew . Glenn Somerville [1 1 WASHINGTON 1] 1996-08-30 Factory orders rose in July and manufacturing surged in the [2 2 Midwest 2] in August , reports said Friday , sparking worries about inflation that battered financial markets for a second straight day . The [3 3 Commerce Department 3] said orders for manufactured goods climbed 1.8 percent in July to a seasonally adjusted $ 317.6 billion -- nearly twice the increase that had been expected . Shipments of everything from new cars to food items rose , as did order backlogs , in a sign that the strength in the industrial sector would continue in coming months . A separate report from [4 4 Chicago 4] area purchasing managers underlined the strength in manufacturing as the group 's barometer of manufacturing in the region jumped to 60 in August from 51.2 in July . A reading above 50 indicates growth in manufacturing . While production and orders rose at [5 5 Midwest 5] area businesses , the prices they paid for goods used in manufacturing remained well in check . Analysts said the reports implied the economy was not slowing down in the third quarter after a burst of growth in the spring , and that the lull in late June and July was more temporary than [6 6 Federal Reserve 6] policy-makers had wanted . " It appears that August is showing an economy again reversing course and is not moving onto a significantly slower track at this point , " said economist Lynn Reaser of Barnett Banks Inc. in [7 7 Jacksonville 7] , [1 Fla 1] . The reports fanned worries on [2 1 Wall Street 2] that the [8 8 Fed 8] , the nation 's central bank , would raise rates next month in a bid to ward off inflation , driving stock and bond prices sharply lower for a second day running . The 30-year [9 9 Treasury 9] fell almost a point , raising its yield , which moves in the opposite direction from the price , to 7.12 percent from 7.04 percent late Thursday . The [10 10 Dow Jones 10] industrial average fell 31.44 points to 5,616.21 after a 64.73-point decline Thursday . A third report from the [11 11 Commerce Department 11] , on July personal income and spending , pointed to a potential slowdown in consumer spending that some analysts said may help moderate growth in the second half . It showed spending rose only 0.2 percent last month to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 5.15 trillion after dropping a revised 0.4 percent in June . Incomes from wages , salaries and all other sources gained 0.1 percent to a rate of $ 6.47 trillion after a 0.9 percent jump in June . July 's slight gain in incomes was the weakest in six months , since January when they were flat . Economist Joel Naroff of First Union bank in [12 12 Philadelphia 12] said consumer spending , which fuels two-thirds of the nation 's economy , may be much slower in the third quarter than in the first half , which should slow economic growth . " The [13 13 FOMC 13] ( [14 14 Federal Open Market Committee 14] ) has been forecasting a slowing in economic activity and moderating household demand will have a large impact on overall economic growth , " Naroff said in a written comment . The policy-making [15 15 FOMC 15] is to meet on Sept . 24 to plot interest-rate strategy . It already has adopted a bias toward raising rates to keep a lid on wage and price rises and help sustain the 5-1 / 2-year-old economic expansion . In an interview on the cable television network 2 CNBC Friday , [16 16 Federal Reserve 16] Governor [17 17 Lawrence Lindsey 17] said there still were " mixed signals " about the economy 's direction . " I think that , on balance , it is looking a little bit on the strong side , " 3 Lindsey said . He added that with expansion as solid as it is and with unemployment so low " the greater risks are clearly that we might see some overheating . " While July consumer spending rose only slightly , there were ample indications that consumers remained confident . The [18 18 University of Michigan 18] 's August index of consumer sentiment , made available on Friday to paying subscribers , rose to 95.3 from 94.7 in July . Reaser said strong consumer confidence coupled with relatively lean inventories were providing manufacturers with a reason to gear up production . " The economy is not going to be expanding at the 4.8 percent ( annual ) rate that we had in the second quarter but it is likely to keep expanding in the 3 percent range , " she said , above the 2 percent to 2-1/4 percent that the [19 19 Fed 19] considers to be non-inflationary . New orders to factories were strong for durable goods like new cars and for nondurables like paper and food products . Orders for durable goods , meant to last three years or more , rose a revised 1.7 percent in July after falling 0.2 percent in June . Orders for nondurables jumped 1.8 percent following a 1.2 percent decrease in June .

 [1 1 Mexican 1] avocados not expected in [2 2 U.S 2] . Maggie McNeil [3 3 WASHINGTON 3] 1996-08-30 [4 4 U.S. Agriculture Department 4] officials said Friday that [5 5 Mexican 5] avocados -- which are restricted from entering the continental [6 6 United States 6] -- will not likely be entering [7 7 U.S. 7] markets any time soon , even if the controversial ban were lifted today . " The opportunity to import ( [8 8 Mexican 8] avocados ) probably wo n't become possible for another year , " said Paul Drazek , senior trade advisor to Agriculture Secretary [9 9 Dan Glickman 9] . " We could lift the ban tomorrow , but that would not mean anything immediately , " said Drazek . " We probably would not see avacados come in until next season , next November . " The 1 Agriculture Department proposed more than a year ago to significantly ease an 82-year ban on [10 10 Mexican 10] avocados . Under the administration 's proposal , the borders to the [11 11 Mexican 11] produce would be opened into 19 Northern and [1 Northeastern 1] states from November through February . The plan has raised a storm of protest from [12 12 U.S. 12] avocado growers , who are largely concentrated in [13 13 California 13] . [14 14 California 14] growers have charged that removing the restrictions , even on a limited basis , would endanger the $ 1 billion [15 15 U.S. 15] industry if potentially harmful [16 16 Mexican 16] insects were brought into the country along with the avocados . [17 17 Mexican 17] officials contend that there is no scientific basis for the ban , and that it is illegal under international trading rules of the [18 18 World Trade Organisation 18] . Proponents of the plan discount the worries of the [19 19 U.S. 19] growers and say the plan has enough safeguards built into it to eliminate any significant threat to [20 20 American 20] producers . Under the proposal , only imports of export-quality avocados growing in approved orchards in [21 21 Michoacan 21] , [22 22 Mexico 22] , the country 's main avocado area , would be allowed . [23 23 Mexican 23] growers and distributors would have to abide by strict rules established by the [24 24 Mexican 24] and [25 25 U.S. 25] agriculture agencies . The California Avocado Commission -- which has spearheaded the opposition to lifting the ban -- said new data the group submitted to the [26 26 Agriculture Department 26] last spring shows the department underestimated the pest problem in [27 27 Mexico 27] and have urged that the agency reopen its study of the issue . The administration is still studying the new data , and officials have said that if experts think the information is significant , the agency could reopen its investigation . But [28 28 U.S. 28] avocado industry sources said that while they may have delayed the plan for a while , they ultimately do not expect the administration to change its position . " From a common-sense view , the department should reconsider this plan , but due to politics they will probably go ahead with this , " said Tom Bellamore of the [29 29 California 29] avocado group . Administration officials said they want to get the issue resolved as quickly as possible , but said there is no timetable they are working under . " It 's a very complicated issue , " said the [30 30 Agriculture Department 30] 's Drazek . " We 'll get it resolved as quickly as we can , based on the best available science . "

 [1 1 U.S. 1] Cardinal [2 2 Bernardin 2] says has terminal cancer . [3 3 CHICAGO 3] 1996-08-30 [4 4 Chicago 4] Cardinal [5 5 Joseph Bernardin 5] , head of the second-largest [6 6 U.S. 6] [7 7 Roman Catholic 7] archdiocese , said on Friday his doctors had diagnosed him as having liver cancer and he had a year or less to live . [8 8 Bernardin 8] , 68 , underwent extensive surgery for pancreatic cancer in June 1995 followed by months of chemotherapy , which he said made him more aware of his own vulnerabilities and the need to minister to the sick . " On Wednesday , examinations indicated that the cancer has returned , this time in the liver . I am told that it is terminal and that my life expectancy is one year or less , " a composed [9 9 Bernardin 9] told a news conference . In 14 years as [10 10 Chicago 10] 's archbishop , he built a prayerful , saintly image and was deeply involved in world church issues and publicly committed to rooting out abuses by clergy . " I have been assured that I still have some quality time left , " he said , saying he would undergo a new form of chemotherapy but his doctors have told him there was only a slim chance of a cure and the liver cancer was inoperable . " It 's not going to be easy to say goodbye to everybody . Death does have some sad dimensions to it but I am a man of faith , " he said . " Death is a natural phenomenom . " He said he would " serve until the end " as cardinal . Pancreatic cancer is among the most deadly forms of the disease , although [11 11 Bernardin 11] 's case was caught early . Surgeons removed a cancerous kidney , parts of his pancreas and stomach , small intestine , bile duct and surrounding tissues . He made a rapid recovery and resumed most of his duties , but then developed a deteriorating condition in his spine that caused him great pain and shortened his height by several inches . He was scheduled to undergo back surgery next month , but that was cancelled when the cancer was discovered in his liver in order to avoid delaying the start of chemotherapy . The spare , soft-spoken son of an [12 12 Italian 12] stonecutter took over the [13 13 Chicago 13] archdiocese , the nation 's second-largest after [14 14 Los Angeles 14] , with 2.3 million parishioners , in 1982 . Ironically , [15 15 Bernardin 15] , who developed a progressive , much-praised programme to deal with pedophilia involving priests , became the highest-ranking church official ever accused of sexual improprieties when a former seminary student leveled charges in 1993 that he had been sexually abused by [16 16 Bernardin 16] during the 1970s . [17 17 Bernardin 17] steadfastly denied the charges and the former student later recanted his tale of abuse . [18 18 Bernardin 18] prayed with him before he died from [19 19 AIDS 19] last year . [20 20 Bernardin 20] , who became archbishop of [21 21 Cincinnati 21] in 1972 , played an increasingly prominent role in the [22 22 U.S. 22] church as a moderate voice of compromise among liberals and conservatives in the ranks of the bishops . This month , he announced that he would oversee a series of conferences to find " common ground " among [1 American 1] Catholics . Previously , he was instrumental in drafting church policy on war , peace and nuclear arms , and for seven years he headed the bishops ' anti-abortion policy committee , espousing a policy describing human life as a " seamless garment . "

 Boatmen 's deal could spark more mergers . Brad Dorfman [1 1 CHICAGO 1] 1996-08-30 The $ 9.5 billion proposed acquisition of Boatmen 's Bancshares Inc. by [2 2 NationsBank Corp. 2] could spark a flurry of other mergers involving [3 3 Missouri 3] banks , which until last year were protected from outside buyers by state regulations . " [4 4 NationsBank 4] just strolled into the [5 5 Midwest 5] and bagged the biggest banking trophy in the landscape , " said Michael Ancell , banking industry analyst at Edward D. Jones & Co . " Whoever wants a big market position in the [6 6 Midwest 6] has to come in and grab Mercantile or Commerce . " St. Louis-based Mercantile Bancorp Inc. , a bank holding company with $ 18.04 billion in assets , was seen by many analysts as the most attractive [7 7 Missouri 7] franchise in size after [1 Boatmen 1] 's . [8 8 Kansas City 8] , Mo.-based 1 Commerce Bancshares Inc. , with $ 9.32 billion in assets , also could help a regional bank establish a strong presence in the lower [9 9 Midwest 9] , analysts added . " It focuses more attention on Mercantile , Commerce and [2 Roosevelt 2] , " said James Weber , analyst at 2 A.G. Edwards & Sons . Roosevelt Financial Group Inc is a $ 9.33 billion asset-St . Louis based thrift . " Now ... the most coveted bank out there is Mercantile , " Weber said . Mercantile and Commerce did not return phone calls seeking comment . Among those seen as having an interest in buying in [10 10 Missouri 10] are Minneapolis-based First Bank System Inc. and [3 Norwest Corp. 3] , Ohio-based KeyCorp and Banc One Corp. , and First Chicago NBD Corp. in [11 11 Illinois 11] . Representatives of [4 First Bank 4] , [12 12 Norwest 12] , [13 13 Banc One 13] and [14 14 First Chicago 14] said the banks do not comment on rumors of possible mergers or acquisitions . [15 15 KeyCorp 15] , contacted by phone , would not comment . With a presence in nine states and $ 41 billion in assets , Boatmen 's was the prize in [16 16 Missouri 16] , where barriers to outside acquirers were brought down last year by a federal banking statute . " [5 Boatmen 5] 's was the plum of [17 17 Missouri 17] and was the plum of the central [18 18 Midwest 18] , " Weber said . Talk that the [19 19 Missouri 19] banks were seeking inflated prices from buyers was seen as a reason a deal has not occurred sooner . But [20 20 NationsBank 20] 's bid , representing a premium of 40 percent for Boatmen 's stock , was large enough to get the deal done . " I think Boatmen 's was shopping itself , and everybody knew if you wanted to be the winning buyer here , you had to make the bid nobody would beat , " Ancell said . But some analysts cautioned that other targets should not expect as large a premium . They also questioned whether [21 21 NationsBank 21] can recoup shareholder value with such a large bid for [6 Boatmen 6] 's . " I think initially some stocks will trade up on sympathy , but the wild premium [22 22 NationsBank 22] put on this deal here , I do n't see a lot of other deals being done at this premium , " said Michael Durante , analyst at McDonald & Co .

 [1 1 Titanic 1] recovery mission is scrapped . [2 2 NEW YORK 2] 1996-08-30 Equipment problems and mechanical failure forced a recovery expedition to give up efforts to retrieve a giant slab of the [3 3 RMS Titanic 3] from the ocean floor , a spokeswoman said on Friday . A 20-ton piece of the [4 4 Titanic 4] 's steel hull , which had been attached by cables to a recovery ship off the coast of [1 1 Newfoundland 1] , [5 5 Canada 5] , fell back to the bottom of the sea , said Erin Purcell of 2 Boston-based Reagan Communications that represents two of the ships used in the expedition . The piece of hull , lifted from the ocean floor by means of several diesel-filled bags , had been stuck about 200 feet ( about 70 metres ) below the water 's surface before it fell , she said . It fell as recovery crews were trying to haul the piece into more shallow water and several of the bags burst and cables snapped , she said . The steel-hulled [6 6 Titanic 6] , thought to be unsinkable , struck an iceberg on April 14 , 1912 , and sank , killing 1,523 of the 2,200 passengers and crew on board . The wreck was located in 1985 . Passengers who had paid $ 1,500 and up to accompany the recovery expedition on two cruise ships had returned back to port on Thursday , Purcell said .

 [1 1 France 1] expels [2 2 African 2] , [3 3 Air France 3] unions protest . [4 4 PARIS 4] 1996-08-30 [5 5 France 5] on Friday expelled another [6 6 African 6] man seized in a police raid on a [7 7 Paris 7] church as about 100 [8 8 Air France 8] workers denounced " charters of shame " used to fly illegal immigrants home . A Guinean man , detained in a round-up in the Saint-Bernard church a week ago , was deported on a scheduled [9 9 Air France 9] flight to [10 10 Conakry 10] after his appeals failed , a spokesman for [11 11 Air France 11] 's pro-Socialist [12 12 CFDT 12] union said . He was apparently the eighth [13 13 African 13] deported from among 210 people evicted from the church after a 50-day occupation aimed at securing residence permits , unions said . About 100 people from the [14 14 CFDT 14] and the Communist-led [15 15 CGT 15] unions marched outside [16 16 Air France 16] headquarters at [1 1 Charles de Gaulle 1] airport north of [17 17 Paris 17] against the use of civilian jets and staff in deporting illegal immigrants . " We must obtain a formal commitment from ( [18 18 Air France 18] chairman ) [19 19 Christian Blanc 19] that no plane , no personnel be used to transform our air companies into charters of shame , " [20 20 CFDT 20] spokesman Francois Cabrera said . He said civilians should not be police accomplices . Twenty-three out of 25 charters flying illegal immigrants home since Prime Minister [21 21 Alain Juppe 21] 's government took office in May 1995 have been civilian jets . The other two were military jets . Separately , Juppe confirmed the conservative government was preparing to submit a draft bill to parliament to tighten laws on illegal workers as part of a crackdown on immigration . " Legislation is insufficient in several areas , notably in those concerning illegal work , " Juppe told reporters .

[3 3 TORONTO 3] 1996-08-30 [4 4 Canadian 4] bonds opened softer on Friday , pulled lower by a sinking [5 5 U.S. 5] market , but outperformed [6 6 U.S. 6] bonds on positive [7 7 Canadian 7] economic data , analysts said . " I think this morning 's [8 8 Canadian 8] numbers were very supportive of narrower spreads , particularly the current account number , " said Jim Webber , director of fixed-income research with TD Securities Inc . [9 9 Canada 9] 's 8.0 percent bond due 2023 fell C$ 0.45 to C$ 101.15 to yield 7.894 percent . The [10 10 U.S. 10] 30-year benchmark fell 30/32 to yield 7.12 percent . The spread between benchmark bonds narrowed 77 basis points from 81 basis points at the close of trading on Wednesday . [11 11 Statistics Canada 11] on Friday reported [12 12 Canada 12] 's current account moved to a higher-than-expected C$ 1.15 billion second quarter surplus from a C$ 1.62 billion deficit in the first quarter . It was the first surplus since the fourth quarter of 1984 . The agency also reported [13 13 Canada 13] 's real gross domestic product rose a weaker-than-expected 0.3 percent in the second quarter or 1.3 percent at an annualized rate . While the data provided support for [14 14 Canadian 14] bonds , both [15 15 Canadian 15] and [16 16 U.S. 16] markets weakened after the release of strong [17 17 U.S. 17] economic data , including a report showing the Chicago Purchasing Managers August index rose to 60 from 51.2 in July . " The purchasing managers ' number is extremely , extremely strong , " said Webber . In other news , the Toronto Bond Traders ' Association said it is recommending that dealings in the [18 18 Canadian 18] bond market end early at 1400 EDT / 1800 [19 19 GMT 19] on Friday . The [20 20 Canadian 20] market typically closes early on holiday weekends and [21 21 Canadian 21] financial markets will be closed on Monday for [22 22 Labour Day 22] . In other prices , the 7.0 percent of 2006 fell C$ 0.28 to C$ 96.89 to yield 7.437 percent . The [23 23 U.S. 23] 10-year benchmark fell 21/32 to yield 6.95 percent . The spread between the two bonds narrowed to 49 basis points from 54 basis points at the close of trading on Thursday . The three-month cash bill traded at 4.04 percent against the [24 24 U.S. 24] three-month bill at 5.26 percent . -- Jeffrey Hodgson ( 416 ) 941-8105 , e-mail : jeffrey.hodgson@reuters.com

Sample: b'1030testa_Consumer'
 Consumer spending , incomes edge up in July . Glenn Somerville [1 1 WASHINGTON 1] 1996-08-30 Consumer spending barely edged up in July , the [2 2 Commerce Department 2] said Friday , as income growth slowed abruptly to the weakest pace in six months . Spending rose 0.2 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 5.15 trillion after dropping a revised 0.4 percent in June . Incomes from wages , salaries and all other sources gained 0.1 percent to a rate of $ 6.47 trillion after a 0.9 percent jump in June . Department officials said July 's slight gain in incomes was the weakest for any month since January , when they were flat . Wages and salaries came under pressure in July as a shorter average workweek and lower hourly earnings cut into paychecks . The department said wages and salaries decreased by $ 6.9 billion in July after climbing $ 45 billion in June . " In July , average weekly hours and average hourly earnings declined , more than offsetting the effect of an increase in employment , " 1 Commerce said . But more money went into savings accounts , as savings held at 5.3 cents out of each dollar earned in both June and July . That was the highest savings rate since October last year , when 5.5 cents out of each dollar earned was being saved . The generally lackluster report on spending and incomes in July had been expected . At the same time , the department said in a separate report that new orders received by [3 3 U.S. 3] factories climbed strongly in July , with widespread gains across most major categories . Orders increased 1.8 percent to a seasonally adjusted $ 317.6 billion , significantly stronger than the 1 percent rise forecast by [4 4 Wall Street 4] economists . That followed a revised 0.7 percent decline in June orders . Commerce said previously that spending at retail stores was up only 0.1 percent in July , partly because of softer sales of new cars and light trucks . In addition , the Labour Department 's July employment report had foreshadowed the muted income growth . It showed average hourly earnings fell in July by 0.2 percent to $ 11.00 and the average workweek shortened to 34.3 hours from 34.7 in June . Gains in personal income , which includes wages and salaries as well as income from sources such as dividends , interest and businesses , are essential for funding consumer purchases , which fuel two-thirds of national economic activity . Spending on all types of durable goods , which includes cars , fell to an annual rate of $ 626.3 billion in July from $ 633.6 billion in June . But spending on nondurable products increased moderately to a rate of $ 1.55 trillion from $ 1.54 trillion in June , while spending for services was up to $ 2.97 trillion in July from $ 2.96 trillion . Payrolls of manufacturing companies rose in July by $ 2.3 billion to an annual rate of $ 678 billion .

 World Markets Overnight Summary - Aug 30 . [1 1 NEW YORK 1] 1996-08-29 WORLD MARKETS ROUND-UP STOCKS GOLD METALS NY Dow close [2 2 London 2] opening LME close 5647.65 ( - 64.73 ) $ 387.70 copper per tonne [3 3 Nikkei 3] latest CRUDE OIL $ 1987.0 20202.87 ( - 350.29 ) Sept Brent zinc per tonne [4 4 FTSE 4] close $ 21.25 $ 1000.0 3885.0 ( - 33.7 ) ----- oOo----- STOCKS SINK AS BOND RATES JUMP ON STRONG DATA [1 Blue-chip 1] stocks sank to their biggest loss since mid-July Thursday as fresh signs of a surprisingly strong economy boosted long-term bond interest rates above 7 percent . The dollar rose slightly against the [5 5 German 5] mark , but edged lower against the [6 6 Japanese 6] yen . The [7 7 Dow Jones 7] industrial average ended down 64.73 points at 5,647.65 , its largest drop since July 15 , when it closed with a loss of 161 points . In the broader market , declining issues beat advances 1,627 to 743 on moderate volume of 321 million shares on the [8 8 New York Stock Exchange 8] . In the bond market , the 30-year [9 9 Treasury 9] bond fell 23/32 of a point , or $ 7.1875 on a $ 1,000 bond , raising its yield to 7.04 percent -- the highest since July 31 -- from 6.98 percent at Wednesday 's close . " Seven percent creates psychological problems and a legitimate competitor for money from equities , " said Ralph Bloch , chief technical analyst at [10 10 Raymond James 10] . " We could carry another 100 points lower in the [11 11 Dow 11] , " he said . " I 'm telling clients things are dicey going into next Friday ( Sept . 6 ) so let 's be careful . " [2 1 Wall Street 2] on Sept . 6 faces the key monthly employment report , which has been known to cause dramatic swings in stock prices . " We had two very strong economic reports , " said David Shulman , Salomon Bros . ' chief equity strategist . " There are more worries in bond land . Fears of a [12 12 Fed 12] tightening next month have resurfaced for the first time since the end of July . " The [13 13 Commerce Department 13] reported that the nation 's gross domestic product expanded at a 4.8 percent annual rate in the three months from April through June instead of the 4.2 percent estimated a month ago . In another report , sales of new homes jumped unexpectedly in July to the briskest rate in five months , driving prices up in a strong housing market . Sales shot up 7.9 percent last month to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 783,000 units -- the strongest since February , when new homes were selling at a rate of 784,000 a year . Analysts said the stock market was also worried about the impact on President [14 14 Clinton 14] 's re-election bid of his top political strategist resigning . [15 15 Dick Morris 15] , who is credited with resurrecting [16 16 Clinton 16] 's political fortunes over the past 18 months by masterminding his turn to the political centre , quit after a supermarket tabloid reported he engaged in a yearlong affair with a prostitute , with whom he allegedly shared confidential campaign documents . Analysts said [17 17 Wall Street 17] had grown accustomed to a moderate [18 18 Republican 18] in the form of [19 19 Democratic 19] President [20 20 Clinton 20] . [21 21 Morris 21] ' departure raised fears that [22 22 Clinton 22] would veer more to the left in a second term . The dollar closed at 1.4772 marks , up from 1.4767 late Wednesday . The dollar slipped to 108.40 yen from 108.45 . Oil markets rose sharply on a combination of low stocks , two hurricanes and allegations of illicit trading by [23 23 Iraq 23] . September heating oil on the [24 24 New York Mercantile Exchange 24] closed 1.63 cents higher at 63.67 cents a gallon , September unleaded gasoline finished 1.39 cents up at 63.72 cents a gallon and October crude rose 44 cents to $ 22.15 a barrel . December cotton closed 0.95 cent higher at 77.06 cents per pound on the [25 25 New York Cotton Exchange 25] despite some easing of concern about the twin hurricane threat to key [26 26 U.S. 26] growing areas with forecasts indicating both storms may remain offshore . Overseas , [27 27 London 27] 's [28 28 FTSE 100 28] index had earlier climbed to 3,8921.1 just below its record of 3,922.1 , before edging down through the afternoon session to finish the day at 3,885.0 , a fall of 33.7 points . In [29 29 Tokyo 29] , the key 225-share [30 30 Nikkei 30] average shed 156.65 points , or 0.76 percent , to end at 20,553.16 .

 [1 1 Pirelli 1] cables look to tap [2 2 Chinese 2] growth . David Jones [3 3 MILAN 3] 1996-08-30 [4 4 Italian 4] tyre and cables giant [5 5 Pirelli 5] on Friday announced its long-awaited move into [6 6 China 6] with a cables joint venture set to capitalise on the rapidly-growing [7 7 Chinese 7] telecommunications market . [8 8 Pirelli 8] is linking with [1 Hong Kong-based 1] group [9 9 CITIC Pacific 9] in a venture to be called the Wuxi Tong Ling Company Ltd , which will operate in partnership with a local industrial company at its existing factory in [10 10 Wuxi 10] , [11 11 Jiangsu 11] province , [12 12 Shanghai 12] . The partners will invest around $ 30 million in the existing copper cable plant at [13 13 Wuxi 13] to update technology and include optic fibre production , with annual turnover expected to reach $ 60 million within the next few years . The move marks a further move by [14 14 Pirelli 14] 's cables division to expand in the fast-growing [2 Far Eastern 2] developing markets with the group already present in [15 15 Indonesia 15] , [16 16 India 16] and [17 17 Malaysia 17] . " This is really positive news for [18 18 Pirelli 18] , and I expect that it will produce one of the best half-year results in late September compared to other industrial [19 19 Italian 19] companies , " said analyst Paula Buratti at [3 Indosuez 3] . She emphasised that the move was positive because [20 20 Pirelli 20] will have management control of the [21 21 Chinese 21] venture , and it also showed another example of [22 22 Pirelli 22] exporting its technical know-how to developing markets . [23 23 Pirelli 23] shares reacted favourable even though talks had been underway for some time and news about a venture had been widely expected . The shares rose 0.2 percent to 2,555 lire by 1350 [24 24 GMT 24] in an easier [25 25 Milan 25] stock market . This will be [26 26 Pirelli 26] 's first industrial involvement in a [27 27 Chinese 27] market where demand for telecommunication networks is expected to grow to 80-100 million new lines between 1996 and 2000 , doubling demand for optical cables . [28 28 China 28] 's second largest telecoms operator Unicom already has a mandate from the central government to establish 15 million new phone lines by the year 2000 , which will necessitate new trunk line systems and local distribution networks . " The starting of this production base in [29 29 China 29] has for our group an undoubted strategic value , representing an important enhancement of our presence in [30 30 Asia 30] , " said [4 Pirelli SpA 4] chairman and chief executive officer Marco Tonchetti Provera . [31 31 Pirelli Cables 31] has global sales of over $ 3.5 billion , and has become a large supplier of optic cables and systems to major telecoms carriers in the [32 32 U.S. 32] , [33 33 Europe 33] and the [5 Far East 5] . [34 34 CITIC Pacific 34] is a major [6 Hong Kong-listed 6] company focusing on infrastruture , trading , distribution and property , with 28 percent of its 1995 profits coming from telecoms . It has investments in several industrial joint ventures in [35 35 China 35] .

[2 2 AMSTERDAM 2] 1996-08-30 A broad attempt to spur activity in [3 3 Dutch 3] bond futures has been delayed to give participants a chance to become familiar with the trading system , the European Options Exchange ( EOE ) said on Friday . Market-making in the rarely-traded FTO contract was expected to begin today , but an EOE spokesman said the 10 banks and brokers involved in the initiative needed time to get accustomed to changes in the electronic trading system . " It 's not ready yet . We found it wise to take some time between the commitment to start and the actual start , " EOE spokesman Lex van Drooge told [4 4 Reuters 4] . He said no date had been fixed yet for the start of price making in the 10-year contract , but the EOE had agreed to speak again to the participants in one to two weeks . Investors in [5 5 Dutch 5] bonds currently use [6 6 German 6] bond futures to hedge their portfolios because the FTO contract is so illiquid . A limited attempt to reinvigorate the contract two years ago failed . -- [7 7 Amsterdam 7] newsroom +31 20 504 5000 , Fax +31 20 504 5040

 Sombre mood on [1 1 Arctic 1] island after plane crash . Rolf Soderlind [1 LONGYEAR 1] , [2 2 Norway 2] 1996-08-30 The windblown , chilly streets of this tiny [3 3 Arctic 3] town are all but deserted and flags are flying at half-mast beneath a brooding , clouded sky . [2 Longyear 2] is a town in mourning , a close-knit community that has been shattered . Disaster struck on Thursday when a [4 4 Russian 4] airliner bringing coal miners to work crashed as it came in to land at the airport , killing all 141 people on board . " It 's a sight I will never forget . I will remember it for the rest of my life , " said Stig Onarheim . He was one of a handful of rescuers who raced to the scene of the crash in a helicopter on Thursday , hoping in vain to find survivors . The plane smashed into a snow-capped mountain on the [5 5 Arctic 5] island of Spitzbergen on Thursday , just east of [3 Longyear 3] . " Imagine a big plane with a lot of luggage and people on board . Think of all that mixed together , with twisted , wrecked parts on the slope , " Onarheim , 29 , told [6 6 Reuters 6] . Police and local officials have sealed off the crash site , protecting it from intrusive reporters and from the polar bears that roam freely across the icy expanses . The dead were all [7 7 Russians 7] and [8 8 Ukrainians 8] , coming to work in the mining towns of [9 9 Barentsburg 9] and 1 Pyramiden . [4 Longyear 4] is a [10 10 Norwegian 10] settlement of just over 1,000 people , but it also feels the loss keenly . " I have trouble finding the words to express my grief . It 's a tragedy for everyone . We know many of the people who live in [11 11 Barentsburg 11] , some of them could have been on the plane , " said Johan Sletten , 52 . Sletten , a caretaker who has lived on the island for 30 years , said the [12 12 Norwegian 12] and [13 13 Russian 13] communities visit frequently , competing at soccer in the summer and with snow-scooter races in the winter . Teenage shop assistant Heidi Groenstein was blunter . " I 'm glad it was not a [14 14 Norwegian 14] plane , " she said . " Just think of it -- a mining village where so many workers die . They must be having a tough time of it now . " [15 15 Barentsburg 15] , just a few hours ride by snow-scooter or 15 minutes by helicopter from [5 Longyear 5] , has asked to be left alone with its grief and told reporters to stay away . Around 100 [16 16 Russian 16] and [17 17 Ukrainian 17] miners were waiting in [6 Longyear 6] to fly home on the plane that crashed . They were given shelter in the town 's church overnight and ate a sombre breakfast before getting on a bus for the airport . Another plane had been sent from [18 18 Moscow 18] to pick them up . At this time of year , the only colour in [7 Longyear 7] comes from the brightly-painted wooden houses . Everything else is muddy , the waters of the fjord leaden . Winter is in the air . [19 19 Barentsburg 19] is an even grimmer place , a run-down testament to the hardships of the new [20 20 Russia 20] . Spitzbergen lies some 500 miles ( 800 km ) off the northern tip of [21 21 Norway 21] and endures one of the most extreme climates on the planet . Inhabited by fewer than 3,000 people in total , it sees the sun for 24 hours a day during summer and is plunged into round-the-clock darkness in the winter months . The terrain is mountainous , the only roads are dirt tracks . [22 22 Norway 22] rules the island group under the terms of a 1920s international treaty which gave many other nations the right to establish setttlements and exploit the coal that is still mined there . Only [23 23 Russia 23] has chosen to do so .

Andy Colquhoun [4 4 JOHANNESBURG 4] 1996-08-31 [5 5 South Africa 5] managed to avoid a fifth successive defeat in 1996 at the hands of the [6 6 All Blacks 6] with an emphatic 32-22 victory in front of an ecstatic [7 7 Ellis Park 7] crowd on Saturday . They scored three tries in recording their highest total against [8 8 New Zealand 8] , salvaging some pride in a season in which the world champions have lost five out of eight tests . It also ended a run of nine successive victories this year for [9 9 New Zealand 9] but arrived too late to prevent a 2-1 series defeat and an historic first [10 10 All Black 10] series triumph on [1 1 South African 1] soil . [11 11 Springbok 11] scrum-half [12 12 Joost van der Westhuizen 12] was his side 's inspiration , scoring their opening try and making the third for flanker Andre Venter from a quickly taken penalty to give his side a 29-8 lead after 54 minutes . Fullback [13 13 Andre Joubert 13] scored the other , scorching in from 40 metres at the start of the second half to add to his three long-range penalties . The [14 14 All Blacks 14] salvaged some pride by scoring two tries from centre [15 15 Walter Little 15] and scrum-half [16 16 Justin Marshall 16] in the final five minutes to close a gap which at one point stood at 24 points . But they generally endured an off-day , highlighted by recalled fly-half [17 17 Andrew Mehrtens 17] who missed five out of eight kicks at goal . Recalled fly-half [18 18 Henry Honiball 18] kicked the [19 19 Springboks 19] into a 6-0 lead after 10 minutes only to see [20 20 Andrew Mehrtens 20] launch a penalty from eight metres inside his own half to narrow the gap . [21 21 Mehrtens 21] missed three further penalties and a conversion in the first 40 minutes which could have put his side ahead , but it was the [22 22 Springboks 22] who looked the more dangerous . Their promise was realised when [2 Joubert 2] made a 40-metre break in the 25th minute and , although winger Pieter Hendriks appeared to knock on [3 Joubert 3] 's reverse pass , [23 23 Welsh 23] referee Derek Bevan allowed [4 Van der Westhuizen 4] to pick up and score under the posts . [24 24 Honiball 24] converted and [5 Joubert 5] kicked a penalty before [25 25 All Black 25] hooker [26 26 Sean Fitzpatrick 26] scored a try from close range on the stroke of half-time to narrow the lead to 16-8 and hint at a comeback . Instead [6 Joubert 6] kicked another long penalty and then raced around the outside of the defence to score the [27 27 Springboks 27] ' second try . A quick penalty from [7 Van der Westhuizen 7] five metres from the [28 28 All Black 28] line set up the third try for Venter five minutes later and when [8 Joubert 8] kicked his third penalty the [29 29 Springboks 29] held an unassailable 32-8 lead going into the last quarter . When the [30 30 All Blacks 30] did break through , it was too late . Centre [31 31 Walter Little 31] followed up [32 32 Mehrtens 32] ' kick to score under the posts and scrum-half [33 33 Justin Marshall 33] forced himself over from a ruck close to the line in injury-time to give them some consolation .  Paper says [1 1 Thatcher 1] 's office consulted astrologer . [2 2 LONDON 2] 1996-09-01 A [3 3 British 3] newspaper said [4 4 Margaret Thatcher 4] was so shaken by an 1 IRA attempt on her life when she was prime minister in 1984 that an astrologer was asked to warn her against future threats . [5 5 The Sunday Telegraph 5] quoted Majorie Orr as saying she did a horoscope chart for [6 6 Thatcher 6] , a [1 Libran 1] , after she narrowly escaped death in the [2 2 Irish 2] guerrilla bombing of a hotel during the [7 7 Conservative Party 7] conference more than a decade ago . Orr said [8 8 Thatcher 8] 's press secretary [3 Bernard Ingram 3] asked her to telephone if she saw any threatening indications in the future . " [9 9 Bernard Ingham 9] told me that if I ever heard anything that indicated danger I was to let him know , " Orr said . Orr said she never had to telephone . She added that the horoscope was purely for security purposes and she was never consulted about political moves . [4 Ingram 4] was quoted as telling the newspaper he thought astrology was " a load of rubbish " and that he could not recall asking Orr to keep a watch on [10 10 Thatcher 10] 's stars . [11 11 Thatcher 11] , dubbed the " Iron Lady " for her driven , forceful personality , was never known to have an interest in the occult and in fact has a university degree in chemistry . Former [12 12 U.S. 12] president [13 13 Ronald Reagan 13] 's wife , 3 Nancy , admitted in her biography 4 My Turn that she regularly consulted an astrologer to help her plan her husband 's schedule .

[7 7 Zycie Warszawy 7] said its own publisher , mineral water firm Multico , and a group headed by [8 8 Polish 8] businessman [9 9 Zygmunt Solorz 9] were forming a consortium which would offer about $ 120 million , with finance provided by BRE . The consortium wanted 40 percent of Ruch 's shares , the state would get 20 percent of Ruch and 40 percent would be offered on the [10 10 Warsaw 10] stock exchange . " This division would guarantee a dispersal of capital , preventing anyone from taking total control over Ruch and dictating market conditions , " the paper quoted one of the initiators of the move as saying , without giving a name . A consortium of press distributor [2 2 Hachette 2] and [11 11 Polish 11] publishers group UWP are seeking more than than 50 percent of Ruch and [12 12 French 12] President [13 13 Jacques Chirac 13] is likely to support its case when he visits [14 14 Poland 14] in September , the daily said . News-stand chain Ruch , which controls about 65 percent of [15 15 Poland 15] 's press distribution market , had a net profit of 16.2 million zlotys on sales of 2.7 billion zlotys in 1995 . It has about 17,000 news-stands and was the country 's sole press distributor before the 1989 fall of communism . [16 16 Zycie Warszawy 16] said the new , open consortium , which also included several listed [17 17 Polish 17] firms , would on Monday inform Privatisation Minister Wieslaw Kaczmarek of its plans . It aims to invest $ 200 million in Ruch over five years -- more than the sum Ruch says it needs to upgrade its outlets . Initially [18 18 Poland 18] offered up to 75 percent of Ruch but in March Kaczmarek cancelled the tender and offered a minority stake with an option to increase the equity . Two consortia -- UWP-Hachette and a consortium of a [19 19 Polish 19] SPC group and [20 20 Swiss 20] firms -- placed initial bids . But after the change of tender conditions [21 21 Swiss 21] investors pulled out and SPC decided to bid jointly with UWP-Hachette .  [1 1 Cuban 1] novelist Jose Soler Puig dies at 79 . [2 2 HAVANA 2] 1996-08-31 One of [3 3 Cuba 3] 's most acclaimed authors , Jose Soler Puig , died at the age of 79 , the official newspaper [4 4 Granma 4] reported on Saturday . Puig 's first novel , " Bertillon 166 , " was published in 1960 , a year after the [5 5 Cuban 5] revolution brought President [6 6 Fidel Castro 6] to power . The book , which has been translated into 40 languages , deals with a day in the life of [7 7 Santiago de Cuba 7] , Puig 's native city , under the pre-Castro government of [8 8 Fulgencio Batista 8] . The titles of his other novels translate as " In the Year of January " ( 1963 ) , " The Collapse " ( 1964 ) , " Sleeping Bread " ( 1975 ) , " The Decaying Mansion " ( 1977 ) and " A World of Things " ( 1982 ) , followed by " [1 The Knot 1] , " " Soul Alone " and , most recently , " A Woman . " 1 Granma called " Sleeping Bread " Puig 's " greatest gift to the modern novel in our [9 9 America 9] . " The author said in an interview shortly before his death that his own experiences had lent his books their strong sense of realism . " I 'm a thief of ideas , " he said . " The stories have been given to me by people . " In the same interview , published by [10 10 Prensa Latina 10] on Saturday , Puig was asked if he feared death . " Death is not a punishment -- death is the end of life 's punishment , " he said .

MANILA 1996-08-31 The detention of veteran dissident Wang Donghai showed [2 2 China 2] 's determination to crush any vestige of dissent during the current profound transitions in the nation 's leadership , a human rights activist said on Saturday . [3 3 Xiao Qiang 3] , executive director of the [1 1 New York-based 1] group [2 Human Rights in China 2] , said Wang 's arrest on Friday appeared to be part of the national " Strike Hard " campaign that has imprisoned thousands and sent hundreds to their death . " [6 6 China 6] is going through this power transition period . He said one of Wang 's apparent offences was to write a public letter in May suggesting that a free press and an independent judicial system were vital if the government really meant to stamp out rampant corruption . [10 10 Xiao 10] said crushing legitimate dissent was only making the problem worse and one day [11 11 China 11] would pay a high price . " Those issues are not going to go away by repression . You only make things more hidden but potentially more explosive , " he said . Wang , 45 , was sentenced last month to one year 's " re-education by labour " but was released because of ill-health . [14 14 Xiao 14] said conditions in the labour camp were so brutal they drove another activist sentenced with Wang to attempt suicide . Police beat Wang and his colleague , Chen Longde , and encouraged other camp inmates to attack them as well , [15 15 Xiao 15] said .

Deborah Charles [3 3 RANGOON 3] 1996-08-31 [4 4 Burma 4] 's democracy leader [5 5 Aung San Suu Kyi 5] hit out at the government on Saturday for recent arrests and jailing of activists , saying the military abused the law to try to crush the democracy movement . " The main purpose of this press conference is to make it known to the world that the authorities are misusing the law all the time in order to try to crush the democracy movement , " [6 6 Suu Kyi 6] told reporters at her [7 7 Rangoon 7] home . [8 8 Suu Kyi 8] said at least 61 democracy supporters had been arrested since May , and about 30 of them had been sentenced , most to long prison terms . In May the government launched a sweeping crackdown on the democracy movement , detaining over 260 members of [9 9 Suu Kyi 9] 's [10 10 National League for Democracy 10] ( [11 11 NLD 11] ) ahead of a party congress . Most were released but several dozen remain in custody . The [12 12 Burmese 12] government last week confirmed the recent sentencing of nine democracy activists who were arrested in the May crackdown , including [13 13 Suu Kyi 13] 's assistant Win Htein . The military government , which in May said it had detained the politicians to prevent anarchy , said the activists were charged with attempting to destroy the peace and stability of the state . But [14 14 Suu Kyi 14] disagreed with the methods , saying officials often arrested [15 15 NLD 15] supporters in the middle of the night , then did not give them the opportunity to defend themselves in trials . " When our people are tried , they are tried in a very secretive way . Their families are not told , " she said . [16 16 Suu Kyi 16] , who spearheads a campaign for sanctions on [17 17 Burma 17] 's government , was under house arrest for six years without being tried before being released in July 1995 . Several other leading members of the [18 18 NLD 18] have served prison terms . The [19 19 NLD 19] party won a landslide victory in a 1990 election but the [1 State Law and Order Restoration Council 1] ( [2 SLORC 2] ) , which assumed power in 1988 after crushing pro-democracy demonstrations , never recognised the poll . " This lack of rule of law is an indication that the authorities are not interested in fair play , " she said . " They are using a travesty of the law to try and crush our movements and to sentence our people to long terms in prison without proper trial . " [20 20 Suu Kyi 20] said once the activists were sentenced , they suffered inhuman conditions and lack of rights in prison . " Almost all of the prisoners start suffering from various health problems after a couple of years in jail , " she said . " Some of our people have been in prison for five to six years . " Most political prisoners are held in [21 21 Rangoon 21] 's [22 22 Insein Prison 22] . Some who have been released have recounted torture methods like sleep and food deprivation and physical abuse . " If there are any more instances of death in custody it will be further proof that a prison sentence for political prisoners is sometimes almost the same as a death sentence , " [23 23 Suu Kyi 23] said . Hla Than , an elected member of parliament for the [24 24 NLD 24] , died in early August after being at [25 25 Insein 25] for six years . His death came five weeks after James Leander ( Leo ) Nichols , a close friend of [26 26 Suu Kyi 26] and [27 27 Danish 27] honorary consul , died while serving a prison term at [28 28 Insein 28] . [29 29 Suu Kyi 29] said the government had increased its repression tactics on the democracy movement because it feared the growing popularity of the movement . But she said she and the [30 30 NLD 30] would not stop their efforts to bring democracy to [31 31 Burma 31] even if it meant more arrests of party members or even herself . " We will carry on . Nobody is free from arrest in [32 32 Burma 32] . "

 [1 1 Chinese 1] police hold veteran dissident . [2 2 BEIJING 2] 1996-08-31 [3 3 Chinese 3] police have detained veteran dissident Wang Donghai , the [1 1 New York-based 1] pressure group [2 Human Rights in China 2] said on Saturday . Police in [4 4 Hangzhou 4] , capital of the eastern province of [5 5 Zhejiang 5] , told Wang 's family that Wang would be sent to a study class , a euphemism for coercive ideological reform , the group said . Police gave no reason for detaining Wang on Friday and would not let his family meet him or say where he was being held , the group said . Police also would not say why Wang was being sent to a study class -- a holdover from the chaotic 1966-76 [3 Cultural Revolution 3] -- or say when he would be released , the group said . Wang 's family and [6 6 Hangzhou 6] police could not be reached for immediate comment . The group demanded Wang 's release and said his detention was a dangerous signal [7 7 China 7] was returning to its [4 Cultural Revolution 4] days . Last month , Wang , 45 , a veteran dissident of the 1979 2 Democracy Wall movement , was ordered to serve one year of " re-education through labour " , but released because of poor health . Re-education through labour is an administrative punishment with a maximum of three years that can be imposed by police without recourse to prosecutors or the courts . Wang was jailed for two years for organising street protests after the military crushed pro-democracy demonstrations by students at [8 8 Beijing 8] 's [9 9 Tiananmen Square 9] on June 4 , 1989 , with heavy loss of life . [10 10 Chinese 10] authorities appeared to be using administrative punishment more frequently to take dissidents out of circulation without having to go through a more complicated judicial process to impose criminal sentences , [5 Western 5] diplomats have said .

Sample: b'1150testa_Automakers'
 Automakers , [1 1 U.S. 1] agency plan air bag safety ads . [2 2 DETROIT 2] 1996-08-31 Automakers , suppliers , insurers and the federal government 's auto safety agency Saturday launched a $ 10 million safety awareness campaign aimed at reducing the number of children killed accidentally by air bags in cars and trucks . Officials said they will work with law enforcement agencies , pediatricians and media to warn parents about the dangers that air bags pose to children and adults not wearing seatbelts . Since 1993 , 24 children have been killed by the explosive force of automotive air bags , which inflate at speeds up to 200 miles per hour . The first portion of the campaign involves pickup trucks equipped with billboards that were driving along some of the nation 's busiest interstate highways during the [3 3 Labor Day 3] weekend , including 1 Interstate 95 on the [1 East Coast 1] , 2 Interstates 80 and 90 in the [4 4 Midwest 4] and 3 Interstate 5 in [5 5 California 5] . The boards read : " Air Bag Safety : Everyone Buckled , Kids in Back . " Janet Dewey , executive director of the industry-funded National Automobile Occupant Protection Campaign , said most of the injuries to children occurred because they were not wearing seatbelts . A child 's chances of being killed in a car accident , whether the vehicle was equipped with an air bag or not , is reduced by 29 percent when they are in the rear seat , she said . The auto industry was about three to six years away from introducing " smart " air bags with the ability to detect the size and position of an occupant and adjust inflation pressures accordingly . Current air bags were designed to halt the forward momentum of an average-sized , unbelted adult male , not a small child . Automakers petitioned the [2 National Highway Traffic Safety Administration 2] to allow them to introduce air bags that inflate less aggressively to help reduce unwanted injuries . " Even if changes are made to airbags today , we 'd still have 20 million vehicles on the road with current technology , " Dewey said . " The public has n't been getting the message . "

Relations between the two countries are currently under strain because of the testimony in a [16 16 Berlin 16] court of former [17 17 Iranian 17] president [18 18 Abolhassan Banisadr 18] . [19 19 Banisadr 19] , an avowed opponent of the [2 2 Tehran 2] government who now lives in exile , accused top [20 20 Iranian 20] leaders of personally ordering the assassination of three exiled [21 21 Kurdish 21] leaders in a [22 22 Berlin 22] restaurant in 1992 . [23 23 Iran 23] has asked [24 24 Germany 24] to extradite [25 25 Banisadr 25] , who is due is due back in [26 26 Berlin 26] next Thursday to continue his testimony . [27 27 Banisadr 27] , who received political asylum in [28 28 France 28] after fleeing there in 1981 , told [29 29 Der Spiegel 29] he did not plan to ask for a guarantee of safe conduct . If [30 30 Germany 30] were to extradite him , he said , it would " lose face before the whole world " . [31 31 German 31] prosecutors have already accused [32 32 Iran 32] 's intelligence minister Ali Fallahiyan of ordering the killing of the [33 33 Kurdish 33] leaders . [34 34 Iran 34] , which denies the allegations , urged [35 35 German 35] authorities to disregard [36 36 Banisadr 36] 's testimony and said it could hurt relations .

 Controversial 1 IRA film screened at [1 1 Venice 1] festival . Vera Haller [1 VENICE 1] , [2 2 Italy 2] 1996-08-31 Dublin-born director [3 3 Neil Jordan 3] says he never lost more sleep over a film than over " [2 2 Michael Collins 2] " , his controversial epic about the [3 3 IRA 3] which has its premiere on Saturday at the [4 4 Venice Film Festival 4] . The film , starring [5 5 Liam Neeson 5] and [6 6 Julia Roberts 6] , recounts the life of [7 7 Michael Collins 7] , the [8 8 Irish Republican Army 8] 's Director of Intelligence who fought for [9 9 Irish 9] independence from 1919 to 1921 . Although not due for release in [10 10 Britain 10] until early next year , some politicians have already said they feared it would fan sectarian tensions in British-ruled [11 11 Northern Ireland 11] . [12 12 Jordan 12] defends his decision to make the film , whose screenplay he wrote himself after years of research , saying it was " more about history than any political statement " . " The film spares neither the [13 13 Irish 13] nor the [14 14 British 14] in its depiction of the savagery of the time , " [15 15 Jordan 15] said in a statement released by [16 16 Warner Bros 16] . " How often has independence been achieved without bloodshed ? Very rarely . " [17 17 Jordan 17] , whose 1992 film " 4 The Crying Game " also came under fire for what was perceived as a sympathetic portrayal of the [4 5 IRA 4] , said 6 Collins was more than just a revolutionary . " He developed techniques of guerilla warfare later copied by independence movements around the world , from [18 18 Mao Tse-Tung 18] in [19 19 China 19] to [20 20 Yitzak Shamir 20] in [21 21 Israel 21] , " [5 7 Jordan 5] said . " 8 Collins would never be a proponent of contemporary terrorism as practised today . He was a soldier and a statesman and , over time , a man of peace . " Leeson , the Northern Ireland-born actor who was nominated for an [6 9 Oscar 6] for best actor for his performance in " Schindler 's List " , plays the lead role in [22 22 Jordan 22] 's film . 10 Aidan Quinn portrays [23 23 Harry Boland 23] , [24 24 Collins 24] ' best friend , and rival for the love of [25 25 Kitty Kiernan 25] , played by [26 26 Roberts 26] . Much of the film was shot on location in [27 27 Dublin 27] with [7 11 Jordan 7] using thousands of its citizens as unpaid extras . A set , however , was used for the fighting scenes . Noting that information about 12 Collins was " as mysterious as the existence he maintained " , [28 28 Jordan 28] said he made some historical assumptions in the film . " I have made choices about certain events based on my own extensive research into his letters and reported speeches , " he said . " I wanted to make this a story as accurate as possible without killing it dramatically and I think I have . It is a very true film . " One of the assumptions is his interpretation of the murky circumstances surrounding the shooting death of 13 Collins , who had broken with his comrades when he sought a negotiated settlement with [29 29 Britain 29] , in an ambush in 1922 . " I have never lost more sleep over the making of a film than I have over ' 14 Michael Collins ' , but I 'll never make a more important one , " [30 30 Jordan 30] said . " In the life of one person you can tell the events that formed the north and south of [8 15 Ireland 8] as they are today . "
